Today I started building the actual agentic reasoning layer of the IPL RAG system. Until now, the project had a functioning ingestion pipeline and a structured SQLite backend, but it still lacked the intelligence required to decide how different types of user questions should be handled. My focus today was to move from a data pipeline into an agent pipeline.

I designed the initial workflow for the agent by separating the process into multiple stages: query normalization, intent detection, tool selection, evidence collection, and final answer composition. This was important because cricket-related questions are not all of the same type. Some questions are best answered using structured SQL statistics, some require retrieval from PDF or text documents, and some depend on fresh web information. A single fixed retrieval approach would fail across these cases, so routing logic became a core part of the architecture.

I also began organizing the project into modular layers so that each responsibility remains isolated and easier to debug. The goal was not just to make the code work, but to make the reasoning path traceable. For this reason, I planned logging and evidence tracking so that every answer can later be inspected in terms of which tool was selected, what evidence was retrieved, and how the final response was formed.

By the end of the day, the project evolved from a database-backed cricket analytics system into the early skeleton of an agentic RAG architecture. This lays the groundwork for more advanced features such as hybrid retrieval, reflection, uncertainty handling, and citation-based answer generation.
